@bmamlin For standard checksum, we use everything that user can add/edit from TB/API.
- `external_id` was missed for names/descriptions, I have added it, will be regenerating checksums
- `child_concept_urls` and `parent_concept_urls` are considered but ignored if they are empty so its same as not providing them if its are not there.

@snyaggarwal, I've started testing checksums for mappings. The first issue I ran into is for `sort_weight`. This property is both a first-class property _and_ an extra property in OCL:

```json
{
  "extras": {
    "sort_weight": 7381
  },
  "sort_weight": 7381
}
```

In my JSON import files for CIEL, `sort_weight` is only a first-class property (not an extra). Since `extras` are included in the checksum calculation, the checksums differ. Would excluding an extra property if named `sort_weight` from the checksum be too hacky?

@snyaggarwal, I was able to validate all CIEL concepts via checksum. It took about 2.5 minutes to fetch concept checksums.

I've yet been able to fetch mapping checksums. Using `/orgs/CIEL/sources/CIEL/HEAD/mappings/?brief=true&limit=1000`, there are 234 pages to fetch. It takes almost 2 hours to get 200 pages. My last attempt fetched 208 pages before crashing with a 502 error.

Any chance we could come up with a more efficient way to fetch checksums? I was kind of hoping I could get checksums (with `id` for concepts and `from url`+`map type`+`to url` for mappings) in 1-2 calls that return in seconds. 🙂

